00056 /**
00057  * \addtogroup  DataTypes
00058  * \brief Data types of the library.
00059  *   
00060  * \description
00061  *
00062  *    The possible values of many types of data are represented with
00063  *    enumerations. This module contains the enum declarations and some basic
00064  *    functions for manipulating them.
00065  */

00067 /**
00068  * \addtogroup  DataInterface
00069  * \brief  Primary interface between computational routines and 
00070  *         actual data. 
00071  *
00072  * \description
00073  *  
00074  *    The routines in this section are the primary interface between the
00075  *    computational routines in the Feature Characterization library and
00076  *    the actual data.  
00077  *
00078  *    There are five major data entities: datasets, sequences, meshes, subsets,
00079  *    and variables which follow this basic hierarchy (the library owns
00080  *    everything):
00081  *
00082  *     - Library
00083  *     - Dataset
00084  *     - Sequence
00085  *     - Mesh
00086  *     - Subset & Sequence Subset
00087  *     - Variable & Sequence Variable 
00088  *
00089  *    The data interface routines allow the calling code to get, query, copy,
00090  *    and delete each of these types of objects. In addition, you can
00091  *    load and write datasets. The objects are
00092  *    manipulated via opaque handles (see \ref Handles). These handles can be 
00093  *    assigned directly using '=', but cannot be checked for equality using 
00094  *    '==', so you must use \ref FC_HANDLE_EQUIV instead.
00095  *
00096  *    As a quick review, the library manages multiple datasets and each
00097  *    dataset can have multiple meshes. A sequence is the coordinates of 
00098  *    a parameter space orthogonal to the space of the mesh. The most common 
00099  *    type of sequence would be the time values of a time series. 
00100  *    A subset is a set of mesh subentities (e.g. vertices or elements).
00101  *    A variable is a function, such as temperature, over a mesh. It is
00102  *    associated with some subentity of a mesh such as vertices or
00103  *    elements. A sequence variable is actually an array of variable handles
00104  *    associated with a sequence, with one variable per step of the
00105  *    sequence. Similiarly, a sequence subset is an array of subset handles
00106  *    associated with a sequence, with one subset per step of the sequence.
00107  *
00108  *    It is very important to note that the library makes a distinction
00109  *    between meta data and "big data", and that access to these is treated
00110  *    very differently.
00111  *    Big data are the really large arrays of data that we want to 
00112  *    avoid duplicating or moving around. Currently, the coordinate arrays for
00113  *    the meshes and the sequences, and the data from the variables, are
00114  *    considered big data and everything else is meta data.
00115  *
00116  *    When users ask for metadata they get copies of the data and can
00117  *    manipulate it however they want, and they are responsible for freeing any
00118  *    arrays. On the other hand, when users ask for big data, they get a
00119  *    pointer to the original data (the names of such routines will end with
00120  *    'Ptr'). Users should treat this pointer as read only.  Users should never
00121  *    free big data directly, but should used the release and delete routines
00122  *    to try free up big data or to delete the
00123  *    entity that the big data is in.
00124  */
00125 
00126 /**
00127  * \addtogroup  Handles
00128  * \brief Data objects handled through opaque handles.
00129  *   
00130  * \description
00131  *
00132  *    Handles are used to look up the appropriate data structure in
00133  *    the library's internals. Handles can be assigned 
00134  *    to (copies contents) with '=', but cannot be tested with '==',
00135  *    use \ref FC_HANDLE_EQUIV().
00136  *
00137  *    All of the handles have the same form
00138  *    (a struct containing the slot id and the sequence id), the library
00139  *    declares them as different types to clarify the user API and to add 
00140  *    more compile time type checking. But because they have the same
00141  *    form, general purpose routines and macros (like checking that a
00142  *    handle is valid) can be written. 
00143  *
00144  *    See \ref DataInterface for an explanation of using the data objects.
00145  */
00146 
00147 /** 
00148  * \name Check that an enum has a valid value
00149  * 
00150  * These routines return true (1) if the int passed is a valid value for the
00151  * enumerated type, and false (0) if it is not. Enum values of the type 
00152  * FC_X_UNKNOWN are considered valid because they are possible values of the
00153  * enum. In many cases you may want to check for a "good" value and should
00154  * check "fc_isXValid(value) && value != FC_X_UNKNOWN".
00155  */
00156 //-------------------------------
00157 //@{
00158 
00159 /**
00160  * \ingroup   DataTypes
00161  * \brief  Verify that the given value is valid for this enum
00162  *
00163  * \modifications   
00164  *    - 8/18/04 WSK, Created
00165  */
00166 int fc_isVerbosityLevelValid(
00167   FC_VerbosityLevel verbosity   
00168 ) 
00169 {
00170   switch(verbosity) {
00171   case FC_QUIET:             // fall through
00172   case FC_ERROR_MESSAGES:    // fall through
00173   case FC_WARNING_MESSAGES:  // fall through
00174   case FC_LOG_MESSAGES:      // fall through
00175   case FC_DEBUG_MESSAGES:    // fall through
00176   // no default case so will get warning if new values added to enum
00177     return 1;
00178   }
00179   return 0;
00180 }

00500 /**
00501  * \ingroup  DataTypes
00502  * \brief  Returns number of topological dimensions for a type of element.
00503  *
00504  * \description
00505  *
00506  *    Returns the topological dimensionality of the type of element.
00507  *    If the type is unknown (FC_ET_UNKNOWN), -1 is returned.
00508  *
00509  * \modifications  
00510  *    - Nancy Collins Created.
00511  *    - 2003-NOV-17 WSK Changed to return topodim instead of
00512  *      passing back out in argument list.
00513  */
00514 int fc_getElementTypeTopoDim(
00515   FC_ElementType elemType
00516 ) 
00517 { 
00518   switch (elemType) {
00519   case FC_ET_MIXED:    // fall through to FC_ET_UNKNOWN
00520   case FC_ET_UNKNOWN:  return -1;
00521   case FC_ET_POINT:    return 0;
00522   case FC_ET_LINE:     return 1;
00523   case FC_ET_TRI:      // fall through to FC_ET_QUAD
00524   case FC_ET_QUAD:     return 2;
00525   case FC_ET_TET:      // fall through to FC_ET_HEX
00526   case FC_ET_PYRAMID:  // fall through to FC_ET_HEX
00527   case FC_ET_PRISM:    // fall through to FC_ET_HEX
00528   case FC_ET_HEX:      return 3;
00529   // no default case so will get warning if new values added to enum
00530   }
00531   fc_printfWarningMessage(
00532      "Warning: invalid value for enum FC_ElementType"); 
00533   return -1;
00534 }

00627   case FC_ET_MIXED:    // fall through to FC_ET_UNKNOWN
00628   case FC_ET_UNKNOWN:  return -1;
00629   case FC_ET_POINT:    // fall through to FC_ET_LINE
00630   case FC_ET_LINE:     return 0;  
00631   case FC_ET_TRI:      // fall through to FC_ET_QUAD
00632   case FC_ET_QUAD:     return 1;
00633   case FC_ET_TET:      return 4;
00634   case FC_ET_PYRAMID:  // fall through to FC_ET_PRISM
00635   case FC_ET_PRISM:    return 5;
00636   case FC_ET_HEX:      return 6;
00637   // no default case so will get warning if new values added to enum
00638   }
00639   fc_printfWarningMessage(
00640      "Warning: invalid value for enum FC_ElementType"); 
00641   return -1;
00642 }

00644 /**
00645  * \ingroup  DataTypes
00646  * \brief  Returns number of the entity type in a type of element.
00647  * 
00648  * \description
00649  *
00650  *    Returns the number of the entity type for a type of element.  If the type
00651  *    is unknown (FC_ET_UNKNOWN), -1 is returned.  If the entity type is
00652  *    inappropriate (e.g. FC_AT_WHOLE_MESH on any type of element, or e.g. 
00653  *    FC_AT_FACE on for FC_ET_LINE) it returns -1. Note, passing
00654  *    FC_AT_ELEMENT will return 1.
00655  *
00656  *    For entity specific behavior see fc_getElementTypeNumVertex(),
00657  *    fc_getElementTypeNumEdge(), and fc_getElementTypeNumFace().
00658  *
00659  * \modifications  
00660  *    - 10/24/2005 WSD Created.
00661  */
00662 int fc_getElementTypeNumEntity(
00663   FC_ElementType elemType,  /**< input - Type of element */
00664   FC_AssociationType assoc  /**< Type of entity */
00665 ) 
00666 { 
00667   switch (assoc) {
00668   case FC_AT_VERTEX:         return fc_getElementTypeNumVertex(elemType);
00669   case FC_AT_EDGE:           return fc_getElementTypeNumEdge(elemType);
00670   case FC_AT_FACE:           return fc_getElementTypeNumFace(elemType);
00671   case FC_AT_ELEMENT:        return 1;
00672   case FC_AT_UNKNOWN:        // fall through
00673   case FC_AT_WHOLE_MESH:     return -1;
00674   case FC_AT_WHOLE_DATASET:  return -1;
00675   // no default case so will get warning if new values added to enum
00676   }
00677   fc_printfWarningMessage(
00678      "Warning: invalid value for enum FC_AssociationType"); 
00679   return -1;
00680 }

00682 /**
00683  * \ingroup  DataTypes
00684  * \brief  Returns the element type of the faces of the element.
00685  * 
00686  * \description
00687  *
00688  *    For FC_ET_PYRAMID and FC_ET_PRISM the face type is a 
00689  *    mix of FC_ET_TRI and FC_ET_QUAD, so the type
00690  *    FC_ET_MIXED is return.
00691  *
00692  *    For FC_ET_POINT and FC_ET_LINE which don't have faces,
00693  *    the type returned is FC_ET_UNKNOWN.
00694  *
00695  * \modifications  
00696  *    - 02/05/04 WSK, Created.
00697  */
00698 FC_ElementType fc_getElementTypeFaceType(
00699   FC_ElementType elemType
00700 ) 
00701 { 
00702   switch (elemType) {
00703   case FC_ET_MIXED:    // fall through to FC_ET_UNKNOWN
00704   case FC_ET_UNKNOWN:  return FC_ET_UNKNOWN;
00705   case FC_ET_POINT:    // fall through to FC_ET_LINE
00706   case FC_ET_LINE:     return FC_ET_UNKNOWN;  
00707   case FC_ET_TRI:      return FC_ET_TRI;
00708   case FC_ET_QUAD:     return FC_ET_QUAD;
00709   case FC_ET_TET:      return FC_ET_TRI;
00710   case FC_ET_PYRAMID:  // fall through to FC_ET_PRISM
00711   case FC_ET_PRISM:    return FC_ET_MIXED;
00712   case FC_ET_HEX:      return FC_ET_QUAD;
00713   // no default case so will get warning if new values added to enum
00714   }
00715   fc_printfWarningMessage(
00716      "Warning: invalid value for enum FC_ElementType"); 
00717   return FC_ET_UNKNOWN;
00718 }

00752   }

00754      "Warning: invalid value for enum FC_DataType");
